{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181011120150|863536155","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Ruben_Kihuen","to":"Ruben Kihuen"}],"pages":{"15275851":{"pageid":15275851,"ns":0,"title":"Ruben Kihuen","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-23T16:15:31Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{short description|U.S. Representative from Nevada}}\n{{Spanish name|Kihuen|Bernal}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Ruben Kihuen\n|image           = Rep. Ruben Kihuen.jpg\n|state           = [[Nevada]]\n|district        = {{ushr|NV|4|4th}}\n|term_start      = January 3, 2017\n|term_end        = \n|predecessor     = [[Cresent Hardy]]\n|successor       = \n|state_senate1   = Nevada\n|district1       = 10th\n|term_start1     = 2010\n|term_end1       = 2016\n|predecessor1    = [[Bob Coffin]]\n|successor1      = [[Yvanna Cancela]]\n|state_assembly2 = Nevada\n|district2       = 11th\n|term_start2     = 2006\n|term_end2       = 2010\n|predecessor2    = [[Bob McCleary]]\n|successor2      = [[Olivia Diaz]]\n|birth_name      = Rub\u00e9n Jes\u00fas Kihuen Bernal\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1980|4|25}}\n|birth_place     = [[Guadalajara]], [[Mexico]]\n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education       = [[College of Southern Nevada]]<br />[[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[University of Oklahoma]]\n|website         = {{url|kihuen.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Rub\u00e9n Jes\u00fas Kihuen Bernal''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|r|u\u02d0|b|\u0259|n|_|\u02c8|k|i\u02d0|w|\u026a|n}}; born April 25, 1980) is a Mexican-born American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|NV|4}} since 2017. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he previously was a member of the [[Nevada Senate]] from 2006 to 2016. He is Nevada's first Latino member of the U.S. House of Representatives and Kihuen described himself as the first \"[[DREAM Act|Dreamer]]\" elected to Congress.\n\n[[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Minority Leader]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] has called on Kihuen to resign in response to sexual misconduct allegations against him by a female campaign staff member, as reported by [[BuzzFeed]].<ref name=PelosiSex>{{Cite news|last1=Nocera|first1=Kate|first2=Tarini|last2=Parti|date=December 1, 2017|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/katenocera/she-says-she-quit-her-campaign-job-after-he-harassed-her|title=She Says She Quit Her Campaign Job After He Harassed Her. Now He\u2019s In Congress.|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=December 2, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Though he publicly refused to resign, he will not run for reelection in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Nevada, 2018|2018]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKihuen was born in [[Guadalajara]], Mexico. His family moved to the United States in 1988.<ref name=\"mjordan\">{{cite news|last1=Jordan|first1=Miriam|title=New Kingmaker: Vegas's Mr. Kihuen Will See You Now|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118644209956489830|accessdate=July 26, 2016|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=August 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\nKihuen's father was a laborer in [[Orange County, California]], before moving to [[Las Vegas]] in the 1990s and becoming a middle school science teacher.<ref name=\"mjordan\"/> Kihuen attended [[Rancho High School]] and was named the 1997\u20131998 Nevada \"soccer player of the year.\"<ref name=\"mjordan\"/> \n\nHe graduated from the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]] with a Bachelor of Science degree in education. While in high school and college, Kihuen volunteered for the campaigns of Senator [[Harry Reid]], Virginia Governor [[Mark Warner]], and Houston Mayor [[Lee P. Brown|Lee Brown]].<ref name=\"mjordan\"/>\n\nAs of 2011, Kihuen was enrolled in the [[Master of Public Administration]] degree program at the [[University of Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Division/Research/Publications/LegManual/2013/ch1.pdf |title=Members of the Nevada Legislature |date=2011 |website=leg.state.nv.us/ |publisher=Nevada Legislature |location=Carson City, NV |page=26}}</ref>\n\n== Early career ==\nIn 2002, Kihuen became a deputy field director for the Nevada Democratic Party.<ref name=\"mjordan\" /> He then served as regional representative to Senate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]].<ref name=\"mjordan\" /> He then worked as student recruiter and academic advisor for the [[College of Southern Nevada]] (CSN).<ref name=\"mjordan\" /> He is a past member of the Clark County Community Development Advisory Committee and the North Las Vegas Citizen's Advisory Committee.\n\n== Nevada legislature ==\nFirst elected to the state assembly in 2006, Kihuen served two terms before successfully running in 2010 to the [[Nevada State Senate]] after the incumbent was [[Term limits in the United States|term-limited]]. During the 76th legislative session in 2011 he was the chair of the Senate Select Committee on Economic Growth and Employment. In the 77th legislative session in 2013, he chaired the Senate Standing Committee on Revenue and Economic Development and served as Majority Whip for the Democrats in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leg.state.nv.us/App/Legislator/A/Senate/Current/10|title=Details|work=state.nv.us|accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n[[File:Ruben Kihuen 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|Kihuen in 2012]]\n\n=== Elections ===\n\n==== 2012 ====\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Nevada, 2012#District 1}}\nIn September 2011, Kihuen announced his intention to run to represent [[Nevada's 1st congressional district]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2011/nov/01/titus-being-pressured-not-run-1st-congressional-di/|title=Dina Titus being pressured not to run for 1st Congressional District seat|author=Karoun Demirjian|work=LasVegasSun.com|accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref> but withdrew a month before filing opened in February 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2012/feb/07/ruben-kihuen-out-cd1-race-clearing-way-dina-titus/|title=Ruben Kihuen drops out of CD1 race, clearing way for Dina Titus|author=Karoun Demirjian|work=LasVegasSun.com|accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref> allowing former Representative [[Dina Titus]] to run without a contested primary.\n\n==== 2016 ====\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Nevada, 2016#District 4}}\nOn March 28, 2015, Kihuen announced he was running for Congress in {{ushr|NV|4}}, seeking to defeat first-term incumbent Republican [[Cresent Hardy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/politics/nevada-sen-ruben-kihuen-announces-bid-congress|author=Myers, Laura|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|title=Nevada Sen. Ruben Kihuen announces bid for Congress|date=March 28, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> He defeated seven other candidates in the Democratic primary on June 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marin|first1=Lesley|title=Ruben Kihuen wins Democratic nomination for Congressional District 4|url=http://www.ktnv.com/news/ruben-kihuen-wins-democratic-nomination-for-congressional-district-4|accessdate=June 16, 2016|publisher=KTNV|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Kihuen spoke at the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]], the only 2016 House recruit to do so.<ref name=\"dnc\">{{cite news|last1=Pathe|first1=Simone|title=Hispanic House Recruit Gets Prominent Speaking Slot at DNC|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/hispanic-house-recruit-gets-prominent-speaking-slot-dnc|accessdate=July 26, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=July 25, 2016}}</ref> During the campaign, Kihuen was on leave from his job at the Las Vegas-based public relations firm the Ramirez Group.<ref>{{cite news|title=Politically Connected PR Firm Subpoenaed in Councilman Probe|url=http://lasvegas.cbslocal.com/2016/09/29/politically-connected-pr-firm-subpoenaed-in-councilman-probe/|accessdate=November 3, 2016|agency=The Associated Press|publisher=CBS|date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> Kihuen won the election by a vote of 128,680 (48.5%) to 118,220 (44.5%).<ref name=\"2016Election\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/nevada-house-district-4-hardy-kihuen|title=Nevada U.S. House 4th District Results: Ruben Kihuen Wins|date=November 9, 2016|publisher=''The New York Times''|access-date=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nKihuen defeated Hardy by just over 10,000 votes. While Hardy carried six of the district's seven counties, Kihuen swamped Hardy in the district's share of Clark County, winning it by over 24,000 votes.<ref name=\"2016Election\" />  He was sworn in on January 3, 2017, becoming the first Hispanic to represent Nevada in the House of Representatives. He is also one of the first two Hispanics to represent the state in Congress; [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Catherine Cortez Masto]] was sworn in the same day.\n\n=== Tenure ===\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance|Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Terrorism and Illicit Finance|Subcommittee on Terrorism and Illicit Finance]]\n\n=== Caucus memberships ===\n* [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalhispaniccaucus-lujangrisham.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Hispanic Caucus|date=|accessdate=15 May 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus]]\n* [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Caucus Members|author=|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Sexual misconduct allegations ==\n{{Quote box\n |quote    =  '''Timeline of allegations'''<br />'''February 6, 2016''': Kihuen follows finance director to her car, and tells her \"You look really good, I'd like to take you out if you didn\u2019t work for me\".  She told Kihuen that she had a boyfriend and left.<br />'''February 19''': Kihuen, while in an elevator with the finance director at the [[Aria Hotel]] on the way to a meeting with [[Tony C\u00e1rdenas]], propositions her and suggests \"we should get a hotel room here\"; she refuses.  While returning to campaign headquarters after the meeting, Kihuen began to touch her thigh and ask if she ever cheated on her boyfriend; she demanded he stop.<br />'''March''': Kihuen asked the finance director for assistance with his computer during call time, when she was looking at the screen, he groped the back of her thigh.<ref name=PelosiSex />\n |source   = \n |width    = 30em\n |align    = right\n |bgcolor  = #c6dbf7\n}}\nOn December 1, 2017, a 25-year-old woman who served as finance director of Kihuen's 2016 congressional campaign accused him of sexual harassment and unwanted touching.  The woman, who joined Kihuen's campaign in June 2015 and left in April 2016, alleges that Kihuen's behavior began in February, that he repeatedly requested that she go on dates or have sexual intercourse with him, and on two occasions forcibly touched her thighs without consent.<ref name=PelosiSex />\n\nUpon resigning from the campaign in April, the woman reported to a mid-level staffer at the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] that Kihuen had made her feel \"uncomfortable\", without offering any further details.  The mid-level staffer proceeded to confer with another mid-level staffer, who in turn called Kihuen's campaign manager, Dave Chase, and informed him of the woman's discomfort around Kihuen.  Chase then confronted Kihuen, who denied that anything had occurred.<ref name=PelosiSex />\n\nIn addition to the finance director's conversation with the DCCC operative, she also documented Kihuen's behavior in a series of March 10, 2016 text messages to a friend, and shared contemporaneous details of her departure with four other individuals at the time.<ref name=PelosiSex /> When asked about the accusations, Kihuen said, \"I sincerely apologize for anything that I may have said or done that made her feel uncomfortable\".<ref name=PelosiSex />\n\nOn December 13, 2017, a second woman accused Kihuen of sexual misconduct. The woman, who asked to remain anonymous, told ''[[The Nevada Independent]]'' that he touched her thighs or butt in three separate incidents, and has sent her hundreds of sexually suggestive [[text messages]].<ref name=\"Nash 121317\">{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/364832-second-woman-accuses-rep-kihuen-of-sexual-misconduct|title=Second woman accuses Rep. Kihuen of sexual misconduct|first=Greg|last=Nash|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corp.|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|date=December 13, 2017|accessdate=December 13, 2017}}</ref> As of December 13, Kihuen has yet to deny or confirm the allegation to the ''Independent''.<ref name=\"Nash 121317\" />\n\n=== Response ===\nThe chair of the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]], [[Ben Ray Luj\u00e1n]], demanded Kihuen's resignation immediately after being presented with the allegations by ''[[BuzzFeed]]'' on December 1, saying that \"If anyone is guilty of sexual harassment or sexual assault, they should not hold elected office, Congressman Kihuen should resign.\"<ref name=PelosiSex />\n\nLuj\u00e1n further punished Kihuen by ordering his immediate removal from the DCCC's Frontline program for incumbents in vulnerable seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/363521-house-dems-scrub-kihuen-from-incumbent-program-after-harassment-allegations?amp|title=House Dems scrubbed Kihuen from incumbent program after harassment allegations|first=Lisa|last=Hagen|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|publisher=Capitol Hill Publishing Corp.|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLuj\u00e1n was joined just after midnight on December 2 by House Democratic Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]], who called for Kihuen's resignation and declared that \"the young woman\u2019s documented account is convincing, and I commend her for the courage it took to come forward\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nocera|first1=Kate|title=Nancy Pelosi Calls On Rep. Ruben Kihuen To Resign Following Sexual Harassment Allegations|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/katenocera/nancy-pelosi-calls-on-rep-ruben-kihuen-to-resign-following|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNevada Democrats were quick to condemn Kihuen, although only [[Jacky Rosen]], a fellow member of Congress, explicitly called for him to resign.  [[Aaron D. Ford|Aaron Ford]], Kihuen's former leader in the [[Nevada State Senate]], told reporters that he was \"deeply disappointed and disturbed\" by the allegations.  Perhaps the most scathing criticism came from Congresswoman [[Dina Titus]], who said that \"many believed Ruben had great potential, but unfortunately his personal behavior has jeopardized his political career\" and that \"zero tolerance means zero tolerance. Ruben needs to step up and do what\u2019s right for the people of Nevada\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ralston|first1=Jon|title=The short, now-unhappy political career of Ruben Kihuen|url=https://thenevadaindependent.com/article/the-short-now-unhappy-political-career-of-ruben-kihuen|website=The Nevada Independent|publisher=The Nevada Independent|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nChase, who managed Kihuen's successful campaign but did not join his Washington office, told ''BuzzFeed'' that he believes the former finance director, and wishes that he \"had known her specific allegations when I confronted Ruben after she left the campaign or in time to stop what took place\".<ref name=PelosiSex />\n\n[[Lucy Flores]], who served alongside Kihuen in the Nevada Legislature and had been his Democratic primary opponent in 2016, said that she found the allegations unsurprising given his reputation in the legislature, where \"even though he maintained a girlfriend, he was known to be very flirtatious and hands on\" and that she had \"personally witnessed him being grabby with young, attractive women\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caygle|first1=Heather|title=Freshman Democrat urged to resign after sexual harassment allegations|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/01/ruben-kihuen-sexual-harassment-allegations-274627|website=Politico|publisher=Politico|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater in the day on December 5, Kihuen gave his first interview<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sanchez|first1=Humberto|title=Kihuen says he won't resign, says leaders asking him to leave knew about allegations but still supported him|url=https://thenevadaindependent.com/article/congressional-hispanic-caucus-will-not-call-for-kihuen-to-resign|website=The Nevada Independent|publisher=The Nevada Independent|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref> since the allegations to [[ABC News]], in which he declared his refusal to resign, instead saying that he \"finds it interesting\" that Pelosi, Lujan, and the DCCC \"knew about these allegations last year\".  Kihuen went on to say that the DCCC and party leadership had investigated the allegations, but that \"they didn't find anything, and they continued investing millions of dollars in my campaign\".  This was immediately denied by both Pelosi's office, which said that \"Leader Pelosi first learned of these allegations from BuzzFeed last week\", and the DCCC, who called Kihuen's statement \"not true\", adding that the DCCC had been \"presented with these disturbing facts for the first time last week, and the chair immediately called for his resignation\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bruce|first1=Mary|title=Nevada Democrat accused of sexual misconduct says he won't resign|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/nevada-democrat-accused-sexual-misconduct-resign/story?id=51599790|website=ABC News|publisher=ABC|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2017, Kihuen announced that he would not seek re-election in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Nevada, 2018|2018]] but later claimed he was reconsidering this decision.<ref>{{cite news|last=Viebeck|first=Elise|date=December 16, 2017|title=Rep. Ruben Kihuen won't seek reelection amid sexual harassment allegations|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/12/16/rep-ruben-kihuen-wont-seek-reelection-amid-sexual-harassment-allegations|work=[[The Washington Post]]|location=Washington, D.C.|access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Hispanic and Latino Americans|Biography|Politics}}\n*[[List of Hispanic Americans in the United States Congress]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://kihuen.house.gov/ Rep. Ruben J. Kihuen] official U.S. House website\n* [http://rubenforcongress.com/ Ruben for Congress] official campaign website\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Nevada/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ruben_Kihuen_%5BD-4%5D}}\n* {{ CongLinks | congbio = K000390 | fec = H2NV00050 | votesmart = 66851 | congress = ruben-kihuen/K000390}}\n* {{C-SPAN|rubenkihuen}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cresent Hardy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Nevada|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br />from [[Nevada's 4th congressional district]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ro Khanna]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=398th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Raja Krishnamoorthi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NevadaUSRepresentatives}}\n{{NV-FedRep}}\n{{Current members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{USCongRep-start | congresses= 115th [[United States Congress]]es | state=[[Nevada]]}}\n{{USCongRep/NV/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kihuen, Ruben}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American politicians of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American members of the United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Nevada Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Mexican emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Nevada Democrats]]\n[[Category:Nevada state senators]]\n[[Category:People from Guadalajara, Jalisco]]\n[[Category:People from the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oklahoma alumni]]"}]}}}}